00:39:39.440 --> 00:39:41.090
JOHN BLOOM: Any other questions?

00:39:41.090 --> 00:39:43.420
CROWD: Yes, hello.

00:39:43.420 --> 00:39:44.560
Hello.

00:39:44.560 --> 00:39:47.190
So security was probably
a primary concern

00:39:47.190 --> 00:39:49.539
when you all were working
on setting up Iridium.

00:39:49.539 --> 00:39:51.080
Can you talk a little
bit about that,

00:39:51.080 --> 00:39:53.080
some of the concerns you
had, some of the issues

00:39:53.080 --> 00:39:56.470
you had to overcome, especially
with traffic like San Diego?

00:39:56.470 --> 00:39:59.020
I'm sure it was kind of tough.

00:39:59.020 --> 00:40:02.920
RAY LEOPOLD: OK, the
Iridium System is actually

00:40:02.920 --> 00:40:06.900
the first commercial use of
both a packet switch network

00:40:06.900 --> 00:40:10.410
and a circuit switch
network integrated together.

00:40:10.410 --> 00:40:13.650
Up until that time, all
the communication systems

00:40:13.650 --> 00:40:15.910
tied to the public
switch telecommunications

00:40:15.910 --> 00:40:19.740
system around the world
were circuit switched.

00:40:19.740 --> 00:40:23.410
When we created the architecture
of the Iridium System,

00:40:23.410 --> 00:40:25.820
we made the constellation
of satellites.

00:40:25.820 --> 00:40:27.240
And the satellites
are six planes

00:40:27.240 --> 00:40:29.698
of satellites that went up one
side of the Earth, come down

00:40:29.698 --> 00:40:32.720
the other with the Earth
rotating underneath it.

00:40:32.720 --> 00:40:36.040
And those six
planes of satellites

00:40:36.040 --> 00:40:38.570
have 11 satellites per plane.

00:40:38.570 --> 00:40:40.630
Each satellite
communicates satellite

00:40:40.630 --> 00:40:41.950
directly in front of it.

00:40:41.950 --> 00:40:45.020
It's zero degrees azimuth
minus 16 degrees elevation.

00:40:45.020 --> 00:40:48.800
The one behind it,
180 degrees azimuth

00:40:48.800 --> 00:40:51.140
minus 16 degrees elevation.

00:40:51.140 --> 00:40:54.217
And the ones to the left
and to the right, well

00:40:54.217 --> 00:40:55.800
the ones to the left
and to the right,

00:40:55.800 --> 00:40:58.190
when the satellites are
coming together at the poles

00:40:58.190 --> 00:41:00.600
and then cross over poles
and go the other way,

00:41:00.600 --> 00:41:04.580
you have the
direction that you're

00:41:04.580 --> 00:41:08.210
going to the other satellite
constantly changing.

00:41:08.210 --> 00:41:11.310
And so those inner
satellite links

00:41:11.310 --> 00:41:13.370
actually change direction.

00:41:13.370 --> 00:41:17.280
We have slotted phased arrays
that change the direction.

00:41:17.280 --> 00:41:20.520
And because the
change becomes so

00:41:20.520 --> 00:41:22.750
excessive at the
high latitudes, we

00:41:22.750 --> 00:41:26.500
shut them off at plus 68 degrees
latitude minus 60 degrees

00:41:26.500 --> 00:41:28.680
latitude, and then
re-acquire them

00:41:28.680 --> 00:41:33.030
when the satellite gets over
to the 68 degrees of latitude

00:41:33.030 --> 00:41:34.640
on the other side of the Earth.

00:41:34.640 --> 00:41:37.520
Well, that entire
constellation of satellites,

00:41:37.520 --> 00:41:40.630
and every subscriber
in the Iridium System

00:41:40.630 --> 00:41:43.250
are in a packet switch system.

00:41:43.250 --> 00:41:46.220
And then each of the
satellites has the ability

00:41:46.220 --> 00:41:47.780
to go down to a gateway.

00:41:47.780 --> 00:41:52.890
And the main gateway is
in the Tempe, Arizona.

00:41:52.890 --> 00:41:55.650
And there's always at
least one satellite visible

00:41:55.650 --> 00:41:57.990
from every point on the
surface of the Earth.

00:41:57.990 --> 00:42:01.080
And so as the satellites go
by, they hand off the gateway

00:42:01.080 --> 00:42:02.570
from satellite to satellite.

00:42:02.570 --> 00:42:04.350
And when we get
down to the ground

00:42:04.350 --> 00:42:07.820
to that switching
center on the ground,

00:42:07.820 --> 00:42:11.870
each Iridium ground station
acts as an international switch.

00:42:11.870 --> 00:42:16.120
It's converted to the
circuit switch system.

00:42:16.120 --> 00:42:20.035
So Iridium was the first
realization of packet switch

00:42:20.035 --> 00:42:23.840
to connect together
with circuit switch.

00:42:23.840 --> 00:42:26.220
With respect to
security, it turns out

00:42:26.220 --> 00:42:28.090
that when you have a
packet switch system

00:42:28.090 --> 00:42:31.080
and you have the geometry
like you do with Iridium,

00:42:31.080 --> 00:42:33.100
you get a certain
amount of security just

00:42:33.100 --> 00:42:35.250
from the basic Iridium System.

00:42:35.250 --> 00:42:39.020
Well, then we also
interweave the bits.

00:42:39.020 --> 00:42:41.360
We use forward error correction.

00:42:41.360 --> 00:42:46.790
The packets are 414
bits per packet.

00:42:46.790 --> 00:42:49.880
The framing for the Iridium
System, for the user links,

00:42:49.880 --> 00:42:51.830
is 90 millisecond frame.

00:42:51.830 --> 00:42:56.360
The time slots for any burst of
energy for one of those packets

00:42:56.360 --> 00:42:58.620
is a 8.28 milliseconds.

00:42:58.620 --> 00:43:01.340
And a lot of 90
millisecond frame

00:43:01.340 --> 00:43:05.795
is guard just so we don't have
any interference from satellite

00:43:05.795 --> 00:43:06.750
to satellite.

00:43:06.750 --> 00:43:10.720
And we do use some of the
guard time in each time slot

00:43:10.720 --> 00:43:13.750
for the ringing system and the
paging system in the Iridium

00:43:13.750 --> 00:43:14.420
network.

00:43:14.420 --> 00:43:17.820
So just the geometry and the
architecture, the interweaving

00:43:17.820 --> 00:43:20.940
forward error correction
affords us so much

00:43:20.940 --> 00:43:23.410
communication security
that we didn't have

00:43:23.410 --> 00:43:25.440
to put a lot in on top of it.

00:43:25.440 --> 00:43:27.810
Nevertheless, the
Department of Defense

00:43:27.810 --> 00:43:29.440
decided they wanted
their own gateway.

00:43:29.440 --> 00:43:32.060
And it's in the
Hawaiian Islands.

00:43:32.060 --> 00:43:34.640
And we put an applicate
on top of the user

00:43:34.640 --> 00:43:37.910
units and then another
applicate in the government

00:43:37.910 --> 00:43:40.620
gateway in Hawaii
that offers them

00:43:40.620 --> 00:43:44.200
communication security beyond
what the Iridium System has

00:43:44.200 --> 00:43:45.245
in and of itself.

00:43:45.245 --> 00:43:46.495
Does that answer the question?

00:43:49.940 --> 00:43:54.350
JOHN BLOOM: Yeah, and Iridium
was the first non-country

00:43:54.350 --> 00:43:56.170
to get it's own country code.

00:43:56.170 --> 00:43:58.360
What's the country
code of the Iridium?

00:43:58.360 --> 00:44:00.530
DAN COLUSSY: It's 814 and 816.

00:44:00.530 --> 00:44:02.840
816.

00:44:02.840 --> 00:44:04.710
JOHN BLOOM: It's the
nation of Iridium.

00:44:04.710 --> 00:44:06.855
DAN COLUSSY: There's
two country codes.

00:44:06.855 --> 00:44:08.480
RAY LEOPOLD: There's
two country codes.

00:44:08.480 --> 00:44:12.290
And then Globalstar has
one that's adjacent to it.

00:44:12.290 --> 00:44:17.412
But the US has country
code 1, single digit.

00:44:17.412 --> 00:44:19.370
There's a couple other
countries that have one.

00:44:19.370 --> 00:44:21.130
Like Russia's 7.

00:44:21.130 --> 00:44:24.954
But some other important
countries have two digits.

00:44:24.954 --> 00:44:26.870
Well, we're kind of down
in the pecking order.

00:44:31.349 --> 00:44:32.640
CROWD: Really fascinating talk.

00:44:32.640 --> 00:44:35.970
So what does it take to
operate the constellation?

00:44:35.970 --> 00:44:38.530
Is there like a
control room that's

00:44:38.530 --> 00:44:41.390
filled with people monitoring
and adjusting things?

00:44:41.390 --> 00:44:42.520
Is it highly automated?

00:44:42.520 --> 00:44:43.870
What does that look like today?

00:44:43.870 --> 00:44:47.162
And how might it be changing
with the new system?

00:44:47.162 --> 00:44:48.370
DAN COLUSSY: Ray, that's you.

00:44:48.370 --> 00:44:49.730
You're the expert.

00:44:49.730 --> 00:44:51.680
RAY LEOPOLD: We
built what we call

00:44:51.680 --> 00:44:56.440
the SNOC-- the System
Network Operation Center--

00:44:56.440 --> 00:44:59.445
in Lansdowne, Virginia.

00:44:59.445 --> 00:45:00.820
DAN COLUSSY: Near
Dulles Airport.

00:45:00.820 --> 00:45:03.030
RAY LEOPOLD: Yeah,
near Dulles Airport.

00:45:03.030 --> 00:45:08.730
And it turns that the satellites
are relatively autonomous.

00:45:08.730 --> 00:45:11.390
And it also turns
out that when we

00:45:11.390 --> 00:45:14.630
looked at the requirements that
came from the communications

00:45:14.630 --> 00:45:16.840
system-- because the
satellites project

00:45:16.840 --> 00:45:18.280
down to the earth's
surface cells

00:45:18.280 --> 00:45:20.200
like a cellular
telephone network.

00:45:20.200 --> 00:45:22.880
But unlike the cellular
telephone network, instead of

00:45:22.880 --> 00:45:24.432
the user moving
through the beams,

00:45:24.432 --> 00:45:26.890
the beams move through the
users because the satellites are

00:45:26.890 --> 00:45:29.510
going 7,500 meters per second.

00:45:29.510 --> 00:45:32.310
And it turns out
that when we looked

00:45:32.310 --> 00:45:34.470
at what the actual
communications system

00:45:34.470 --> 00:45:38.990
requirement was, it
wasn't that tight.

00:45:38.990 --> 00:45:42.640
What we learned was we
save fuel on the satellite

00:45:42.640 --> 00:45:46.300
by updating the position of
the satellite more frequently.

00:45:46.300 --> 00:45:48.900
And so when you think about
it, the communications system

00:45:48.900 --> 00:45:52.760
needed each satellite
to be in a certain area

00:45:52.760 --> 00:45:56.110
in space that looked
like a sausage.

00:45:56.110 --> 00:45:59.762
And as long as the satellite
was in its sausage,

00:45:59.762 --> 00:46:02.540
the communications
system would work OK.

00:46:02.540 --> 00:46:07.420
Well, we save fuel by making
that sausage real small.

00:46:07.420 --> 00:46:10.810
And we do the normal
corrections in the polar regions

00:46:10.810 --> 00:46:12.660
when we shut down cells.

00:46:12.660 --> 00:46:14.480
Because we can have
a lot of satellites

00:46:14.480 --> 00:46:16.240
over a pole at any one time.

00:46:16.240 --> 00:46:19.890
And only one cell needs to be
on in that particular region.

00:46:19.890 --> 00:46:23.020
So when we have those
userlinks turned off,

00:46:23.020 --> 00:46:25.350
we can do some
small corrections.

00:46:25.350 --> 00:46:30.220
And as a result, we keep a
very tight orbit control.

00:46:30.220 --> 00:46:32.640
The attitude is
maintained primarily

00:46:32.640 --> 00:46:34.860
with the single pitch
and momentum wheel

00:46:34.860 --> 00:46:36.150
that we have on the satellite.

00:46:36.150 --> 00:46:41.260
It's about a three-pound
mass momentum wheel.

00:46:41.260 --> 00:46:46.050
And we also augment that
with the signal instruction

00:46:46.050 --> 00:46:47.670
in the satellite links.

00:46:47.670 --> 00:46:50.575
We've actually had momentum
wheels fail on satellites

00:46:50.575 --> 00:46:54.280
when we continue to keep
the satellite in orbit

00:46:54.280 --> 00:46:57.840
by doing the attitude and orbit
adjustments with knowledge

00:46:57.840 --> 00:47:01.280
of what we get from near
satellite [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:01.280 --> 00:47:04.950
DAN COLUSSY: That was the
number one issue when we first

00:47:04.950 --> 00:47:06.430
took over Iridium.

00:47:06.430 --> 00:47:08.890
I asked the CEO who was
retiring at that time

00:47:08.890 --> 00:47:11.510
w what's the number one
problem we're going to have.

00:47:11.510 --> 00:47:14.270
And he said, these
momentum wheels will fail.

00:47:14.270 --> 00:47:15.940
They're mechanical devices.

00:47:15.940 --> 00:47:17.869
And we've already
lost a few of them.

00:47:17.869 --> 00:47:19.910
And he said, you're going
to lose a lot of these.

00:47:19.910 --> 00:47:22.720
And it's going to
really screw things up.

00:47:22.720 --> 00:47:24.680
So I brought Boeing in.

00:47:24.680 --> 00:47:26.180
You guys had left by then.

00:47:26.180 --> 00:47:30.280
And you know, [INAUDIBLE]
retro rockets.

00:47:30.280 --> 00:47:34.960
When those things
fail, it's on wheels

00:47:34.960 --> 00:47:36.860
to position the satellites.

00:47:36.860 --> 00:47:39.519
And they came up with software
so that any time-- and I

00:47:39.519 --> 00:47:40.810
think we had lost six or eight.

00:47:40.810 --> 00:47:44.110
I'm not sure where we are today,
Ray, but quite a few of them.

00:47:44.110 --> 00:47:49.770
And the software takes over.

00:47:49.770 --> 00:47:55.510
And it keeps it in position
so the solar panels always

00:47:55.510 --> 00:47:57.680
get the sun and so forth.

00:47:57.680 --> 00:47:59.020
So that's been a lifesaver.

00:47:59.020 --> 00:48:02.970
I mean, that would have
been a real disaster.

00:48:02.970 --> 00:48:06.340
And I think the big thing
that Ray designed into this

00:48:06.340 --> 00:48:08.580
was the fact that we
can change the software

00:48:08.580 --> 00:48:09.680
in the constellation.

00:48:09.680 --> 00:48:16.270
When they go to the North Pole,
we have several ground stations

00:48:16.270 --> 00:48:19.450
in a location within
the Arctic Circle.

00:48:19.450 --> 00:48:21.680
And we sent up new software.

00:48:21.680 --> 00:48:23.440
We've done them dozens of times.

00:48:23.440 --> 00:48:27.780
And every time we have a major
crisis, technical crisis,

00:48:27.780 --> 00:48:29.200
we figure it out.

00:48:29.200 --> 00:48:33.200
Our group of engineers
down in Tempe-- actually,

00:48:33.200 --> 00:48:35.760
Chandler, Arizona.

00:48:35.760 --> 00:48:39.710
And we can send that
new software up.

00:48:39.710 --> 00:48:41.439
And that's very unique.

00:48:41.439 --> 00:48:43.105
I don't think there's
a satellite system

00:48:43.105 --> 00:48:46.420
today-- Ray, you might know
this better than I-- who

00:48:46.420 --> 00:48:49.480
has this capability where
we can send up new software,

00:48:49.480 --> 00:48:51.790
can take care of anomalies.

00:48:51.790 --> 00:48:54.450
And that's worked
probably hundreds of times

00:48:54.450 --> 00:48:58.960
in the last 15 years
where we saw a problem

00:48:58.960 --> 00:49:04.702
and we could fix it by
sending up new software.

00:49:04.702 --> 00:49:07.160
JACOB: I am fortunate enough
to have both hosted this event

00:49:07.160 --> 00:49:12.180
and get the last question before
we wrap up and go to signing.

00:49:12.180 --> 00:49:14.700
I'm actually-- as much as I
am an engineer and curious

00:49:14.700 --> 00:49:16.330
about all the
engineering details,

00:49:16.330 --> 00:49:20.390
I'm fascinated by the show
of will and confidence

00:49:20.390 --> 00:49:24.089
that you, Dan, put into
resurrecting this project,

00:49:24.089 --> 00:49:26.380
especially against all of
the odds that John has talked

00:49:26.380 --> 00:49:30.270
about, including the purchase
price, which was, as you noted,

00:49:30.270 --> 00:49:31.820
like half a penny on the dollar.

00:49:31.820 --> 00:49:34.153
An incredible purchase price,
but still a lot of money--

00:49:34.153 --> 00:49:37.510
not money you had to
follow your vision, Ray.

00:49:37.510 --> 00:49:42.330
So what made formal this
notion that you were really

00:49:42.330 --> 00:49:43.890
going to do this?

00:49:43.890 --> 00:49:46.396
What forced your, sort
of, to take this action?

00:49:46.396 --> 00:49:48.270
DAN COLUSSY: I think it
goes back to the days

00:49:48.270 --> 00:49:51.470
that I ran Pan American World
Airways, which we flew to 120

00:49:51.470 --> 00:49:52.890
cities all over the world.

00:49:52.890 --> 00:49:57.300
And we had a patchwork
terrestrial system.

00:49:57.300 --> 00:49:59.750
Every system you could think of.

00:49:59.750 --> 00:50:03.240
And it worked most of the
time, but not all the time.

00:50:03.240 --> 00:50:06.820
And so suddenly, I hear
about this system--

00:50:06.820 --> 00:50:10.860
66 satellites in the sky that
are working all the time.

00:50:10.860 --> 00:50:11.730
And it's beautiful.

00:50:11.730 --> 00:50:15.600
And it can communicate with
airplanes, ground stations,

00:50:15.600 --> 00:50:18.120
ships, whoever.

00:50:18.120 --> 00:50:21.960
And somebody says, they're
going to destroy this.

00:50:21.960 --> 00:50:22.469
Why is that?

00:50:22.469 --> 00:50:24.260
That's the stupidest
think I've ever heard.

00:50:24.260 --> 00:50:27.180
I mean, they spent $6
billion on it already.

00:50:27.180 --> 00:50:29.840
And so I just got
very interested

00:50:29.840 --> 00:50:35.000
and made them an
offer-- $25 million.

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:37.510
And of course the banks who
were the secured creditors

00:50:37.510 --> 00:50:39.210
said this is chump change.

00:50:39.210 --> 00:50:41.550
Forget it.

00:50:41.550 --> 00:50:43.080
And I said, well,
that's all I have.

00:50:43.080 --> 00:50:43.610
I'm sorry.

00:50:43.610 --> 00:50:49.500
So they accepted it.

00:50:49.500 --> 00:50:53.070
But it was really not that
moment specific so much.

00:50:53.070 --> 00:50:59.060
But it was really my-- I have
to say it was altruistic.

00:50:59.060 --> 00:51:01.170
Because every time
I said in public,

00:51:01.170 --> 00:51:04.550
people looked a
little strange at me.

00:51:04.550 --> 00:51:10.844
But it just seemed
complete insanity

00:51:10.844 --> 00:51:13.260
that you would take this system
that's working technically

00:51:13.260 --> 00:51:14.970
beautifully.

00:51:14.970 --> 00:51:17.250
And because it had
a bad business plan,

00:51:17.250 --> 00:51:19.704
they were going to destroy it.

00:51:19.704 --> 00:51:21.610
And it just was so stupid to me.

00:51:21.610 --> 00:51:24.310
I couldn't believe it.

00:51:24.310 --> 00:51:27.680
So I just got in the fray
and started making offers

00:51:27.680 --> 00:51:32.150
and ran into lots
of difficulties.

00:51:32.150 --> 00:51:35.100
But at the end of
the day, it survived.

00:51:35.100 --> 00:51:38.420
And we own the system
for $25 million.

00:51:38.420 --> 00:51:40.430
They sort of ran out
of money and said,

00:51:40.430 --> 00:51:42.060
[INAUDIBLE] with the banks.

00:51:42.060 --> 00:51:45.420
Oh, the 25 by the
way, I can only

00:51:45.420 --> 00:51:47.230
give you six and a half cash.

00:51:47.230 --> 00:51:53.360
And would you take and
$18.5 million loan 10%?

00:51:53.360 --> 00:51:55.830
So this woman who was in charge
of a consortium of 38 banks

00:51:55.830 --> 00:51:57.430
said, you've got to be kidding.

00:51:57.430 --> 00:51:58.290
I said no.

00:52:01.150 --> 00:52:03.070
And [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:03.070 --> 00:52:06.300
JOHN BLOOM: And
actually, years later,

00:52:06.300 --> 00:52:08.230
a business columnist
for "USA Today"

00:52:08.230 --> 00:52:12.810
was looking for a parallel
in terms of a resource that

00:52:12.810 --> 00:52:15.760
was bought for such
a low price that

00:52:15.760 --> 00:52:19.210
resulted to be as valuable
as it turned out to be.

00:52:19.210 --> 00:52:20.600
The only parallel
they could find

00:52:20.600 --> 00:52:21.955
was the Louisiana Purchase.

00:52:21.955 --> 00:52:24.330
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:24.330 --> 00:52:26.930
And I should say, in
terms of altruism,

00:52:26.930 --> 00:52:30.260
there were four or five
people in the government-- not

00:52:30.260 --> 00:52:32.520
famous people in the
government, not the top people

00:52:32.520 --> 00:52:34.910
in the government, but a
person at the White House,

00:52:34.910 --> 00:52:38.580
a person at the FCC, and
a person in the Pentagon

00:52:38.580 --> 00:52:39.942
who were not well known.

00:52:39.942 --> 00:52:41.150
I could tell you their names.

00:52:41.150 --> 00:52:41.983
They're in the book.

00:52:41.983 --> 00:52:46.070
But you wouldn't know
them-- who fought like crazy

00:52:46.070 --> 00:52:47.970
to make sure these
things weren't crashed.

00:52:47.970 --> 00:52:49.600
And even after the
whole world was

00:52:49.600 --> 00:52:52.560
preparing for the destruction
of the constellation.

00:52:52.560 --> 00:52:55.120
As I said, they sent
out messages to Russia

00:52:55.120 --> 00:52:57.430
saying it's going to
happen on a certain day.

00:52:57.430 --> 00:52:59.820
The software was written.

00:52:59.820 --> 00:53:03.120
The suicide software
was written.

00:53:03.120 --> 00:53:05.550
And there were these
three or four people.

00:53:05.550 --> 00:53:07.340
And when I interviewed
Kathy Brown,

00:53:07.340 --> 00:53:11.250
who was the Chief of Staff
at the FCC, about this,

00:53:11.250 --> 00:53:14.340
she said, you know, when
you spend your whole life

00:53:14.340 --> 00:53:17.860
in government service,
there's a lot of gray areas.

00:53:17.860 --> 00:53:21.350
And there's very few things
where at the end of the day,

00:53:21.350 --> 00:53:25.200
you can say, I'm proud to
have been part of that.

00:53:25.200 --> 00:53:29.630
But I'm proud to be one
of the saviors of Iridium.

00:53:29.630 --> 00:53:32.670
And that's the way--
these government people,

00:53:32.670 --> 00:53:35.930
they didn't benefit a
single penny from it.

00:53:35.930 --> 00:53:38.910
But they were just like,
this is outrageous.

00:53:38.910 --> 00:53:43.060
The White House economist who
was involved was told strictly

00:53:43.060 --> 00:53:45.540
by the White House
legal office, do not

00:53:45.540 --> 00:53:47.910
get involved in the bankruptcy.

00:53:47.910 --> 00:53:51.740
It's unethical.

00:53:51.740 --> 00:53:54.410
All you can get involved
in is public safety.

00:53:54.410 --> 00:53:56.730
And she just said, screw that.

00:53:56.730 --> 00:53:58.550
I'm getting involved
in the bankruptcy.

00:53:58.550 --> 00:54:01.210
And she was one
of the key people

00:54:01.210 --> 00:54:03.450
that set up the
key meetings that

00:54:03.450 --> 00:54:07.680
caused the system to be saved.

00:54:07.680 --> 00:54:10.940
And a lot of these people
they were dealing with

00:54:10.940 --> 00:54:17.170
were veteran politicians who
just see what's in the wind

00:54:17.170 --> 00:54:19.780
and decide whether they want
to risk their career on this

00:54:19.780 --> 00:54:22.489
or whether it's worth
fighting for or whatever.

00:54:22.489 --> 00:54:24.530
And you had these lower
level people pushing them

00:54:24.530 --> 00:54:25.849
saying, do the right thing.

00:54:25.849 --> 00:54:26.640
Do the right thing.

00:54:26.640 --> 00:54:27.400
Do the right thing.

00:54:27.400 --> 00:54:27.920
Save it.

00:54:27.920 --> 00:54:28.350
Save it.

00:54:28.350 --> 00:54:28.850
Save it.

00:54:28.850 --> 00:54:29.380
Save it.

00:54:29.380 --> 00:54:30.389
Until finally--

00:54:30.389 --> 00:54:31.680
DAN COLUSSY: It saved billions.

00:54:31.680 --> 00:54:36.230
JOHN BLOOM: The higher level
people finally at the very end,

00:54:36.230 --> 00:54:42.260
after meeting in the White House
Situation Room with 12 agencies

00:54:42.260 --> 00:54:46.930
there, finally did
the right thing.

00:54:46.930 --> 00:54:49.070
And throughout that
period, every day,

00:54:49.070 --> 00:54:52.880
Motorola was saying, OK, we're
destroying it on Tuesday.

00:54:52.880 --> 00:54:54.580
OK, we're destroying
it next week.

00:54:54.580 --> 00:54:58.835
I think they threatened
18, 19 times to destroy it.

00:54:58.835 --> 00:55:00.710
DAN COLUSSY: The only
other thing I would add

00:55:00.710 --> 00:55:04.590
is that we don't have
exact figures on this,

00:55:04.590 --> 00:55:06.610
but there are
thousands and thousands

00:55:06.610 --> 00:55:11.520
of lives that have been
Iridium Constellation

00:55:11.520 --> 00:55:14.530
all over the world, all
kinds of circumstances.

00:55:14.530 --> 00:55:18.500
And there has been
so much communication

00:55:18.500 --> 00:55:22.285
from these very remote parts of
the world that would never have

00:55:22.285 --> 00:55:24.500
had any means to communicate.

00:55:24.500 --> 00:55:27.730
And this is really
very gratifying to me.

00:55:27.730 --> 00:55:31.170
Because now, starting
September of this year,

00:55:31.170 --> 00:55:32.920
we're going to put up
the next generation.

00:55:32.920 --> 00:55:36.465
It's another $3 or $4 billion.

00:55:36.465 --> 00:55:38.730
But we have a cash
flow now to do.

00:55:38.730 --> 00:55:46.510
Because now, we have 5,000 plus
people actually paying money.

00:55:46.510 --> 00:55:49.240
And when we get to the
next generation which

00:55:49.240 --> 00:55:55.081
will be 15 or 20 years from now,
we'll have so much cash flow,

00:55:55.081 --> 00:55:56.080
this won't be a problem.

00:55:56.080 --> 00:56:02.850
So now we have a system
that's in perpetuity.

00:56:02.850 --> 00:56:07.270
And that to me is I think
the greatest satisfaction.

00:56:07.270 --> 00:56:09.399
And Ray, I'm sure
you can elaborate.

00:56:09.399 --> 00:56:11.690
RAY LEOPOLD: Let me say on
behalf of Bary Bertiger, Ken

00:56:11.690 --> 00:56:14.500
Peterson, and I who created the
system and the couple thousand

00:56:14.500 --> 00:56:17.760
people who brought
it into existence,

00:56:17.760 --> 00:56:20.185
thank you, Dan Colussy.

00:56:20.185 --> 00:56:21.560
JOHN BLOOM: I
should also mention

00:56:21.560 --> 00:56:25.100
that the Malaysian airliner that
went off the grid and was never

00:56:25.100 --> 00:56:26.590
